<subSubSection id="C30F6558FFEA823AFF45FC2E5EC797E9" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFF45FC2E5EC797E9" blockId="10.[160,814,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF45FC2E5D199794" bold="true" box="[184,322,922,944]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Phenology—</emphasis>
Flowering specimens have been collected in Apr. and Dec.; fruits have been collected in Apr.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F6558FFEA823AFF45FC615EB692ED" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFF45FC615E6791F9" blockId="10.[160,814,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF45FC615DF697CE" bold="true" box="[184,429,981,1002]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Conservation Status—</emphasis>
According to the IUCN red list categories (
<bibRefCitation id="EF844B22FFEA823AFF07FC475D2D902D" author="IUCN" box="[250,374,1011,1033]" firstAuthor="IUCN" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" publicationUrl="fromhttp://intranet.iucn.org/webfiles/doc/SSC/RedList/RedListGuidelines.pdf." refId="ref28409" refString="IUCN. 2010. Guidelines for Using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 8. 0. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee in March 2010. Downloadable fromhttp: // intranet. iucn. org / webfiles / doc / SSC / RedList / RedListGuidelines. pdf." title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 8. 0. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee in March 2010" type="book" year="2010">IUCN 2010</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFE7AFC475E70902C" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[391,555,1011,1032]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFE7AFC475E70902C" box="[391,555,1011,1032]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">S. dolichorhachis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is classified as B1a+biii (critically endangered). This species is only known from five widely scattered locations, two of which are in western 
<collectingCountry id="F3027643FFEA823AFF5DFBFF5CA29045" box="[160,249,1099,1121]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, an area that continues to experience extreme habitat degradation (
<bibRefCitation id="EF844B22FFEA823AFEA0FBDC5E29905A" author="Dodson and Gentry" box="[349,626,1128,1150]" firstAuthor="Dodson" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" pagination="273 - 295" part="78" refId="ref28251" refString="Dodson, C. H. and A. H. Gentry. 1991. Biological extinction in western Ecuador. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 78: 273 - 295." title="Biological extinction in western Ecuador" type="journal article" year="1991">Dodson and Gentry 1991</bibRefCitation>
). The location at Limoncocha is in the center of an oil field, continued development of which is encroaching on all sides of the 4,600 ha Reserva Biológica Limoncocha (E. J. Tepe, pers. obs.). Despite its broad distribution, only five collections of this species are known, suggesting that it occurs at low densities, and appears to have been rare even at the time of collection. The label on the 
<typeStatus id="54AE8871FFEA823AFF3AFA825CAD916F" box="[199,246,1334,1355]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">type</typeStatus>
specimen notes 
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFE59FA825E3F916F" box="[420,612,1333,1355]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">in silvestris, rarium</emphasis>
(and 
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFD5CFA825CB8914C" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">in silvis rarissimum</emphasis>
on some of the isotypes). 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFDF7FAE75EAE914C" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[522,757,1363,1384]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFDF7FAE75EAE914C" box="[522,757,1363,1384]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Solanum dolichorhachis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected near the Laguna de Limoncocha near the Río 
<collectingRegion id="49D1F831FFEA823AFD10FAC55F7391A2" box="[749,808,1393,1414]" country="Ecuador" name="Napo" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Napo</collectingRegion>
in 1974 (
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFEFCFA3A5E4A9187" box="[257,529,1421,1443]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">B. A. Drummond III 7329</emphasis>
, MO); however, EJT was unable to relocate this species during a five day visit to the Reserva Biológica Limoncocha in 2009.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFF45FA515EB692ED" blockId="10.[160,814,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<bibRefCitation id="EF844B22FFEA823AFF45FA515D3391D8" author="Montufar" box="[184,360,1509,1532]" editor="R. Valencia &amp; N. Pitman &amp; S. Leon-Yanes &amp; P. M. Jorgensen" firstAuthor="Montufar" journalOrPublisher="Quito: Herbario QCA, Pontifica Universidad Catolica del Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" pagination="411 - 417" refId="ref28685" refString="Montufar, R. 2000. Solanaceae. Pp. 411 - 417 in Libro Rojo de las plantas endemicas del Ecuador 2000, eds. R. Valencia, N. Pitman, S. Leon-Yanes, and P. M. Jorgensen. Quito: Herbario QCA, Pontifica Universidad Catolica del Ecuador." title="Solanaceae" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Libro Rojo de las plantas endemicas del Ecuador 2000" year="2000">Montúfar (2000)</bibRefCitation>
listed 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFE55FA525E1091DE" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[424,587,1509,1531]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFE55FA525E1091DE" box="[424,587,1509,1531]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">S. dolichorhachis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a critically endangered species endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="F3027643FFEA823AFE48F9B75E54923D" box="[437,527,1539,1561]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. If the Peruvian collection is, in fact, a population of 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFE3FF9945E339211" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[450,616,1568,1589]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFE3FF9945E339211" box="[450,616,1568,1589]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">S. dolichorhachis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below), then the species is more widespread than previously believed. Nevertheless, based on the number of collections available for this species, we believe that it is critically endangered, especially in western 
<collectingCountry id="F3027643FFEA823AFEA6F9215DEF928F" box="[347,436,1685,1707]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
where the 
<typeStatus id="54AE8871FFEA823AFDCDF9225E04928F" box="[560,607,1686,1707]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">type</typeStatus>
was collected and which has experienced tremendous habitat destruction.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F6558FFEA823AFF45F9645E729327" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFF45F9645E729327" blockId="10.[160,814,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF45F9645D1E92C2" bold="true" box="[184,325,1744,1766]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Etymology—</emphasis>
The epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFE30F9645E0C92C1" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[461,599,1744,1765]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFE30F9645E0C92C1" box="[461,599,1744,1765]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">dolichorhachis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the long, slender inflorescences of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30F6558FFEA823AFF45F8BF5F9A96E2" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFF45F8BF5DE493F4" blockId="10.[160,814,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF45F8BF5DA39304" box="[184,504,1803,1824]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF45F8BF5D549304" bold="true" box="[184,271,1803,1824]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Notes—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFEF2F8BF5DA39304" authorityName="Bitter" authorityYear="2011" box="[271,504,1803,1824]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dolichorhachis">Solanum dolichorhachis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is a climbing species recognizable by the long and slender inflorescences, small stellate flowers, spindle-shaped fruits, and the simple, usually large leaves with distinctly oblique bases. This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C154D50FFEA823AFF1DF8345D0293B1" box="[224,345,1920,1941]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pacificum">
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFF1DF8345D0293B1" box="[224,345,1920,1941]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">S. pacificum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the wiry-woody stems, densely shortpubescent inflorescences and young stems, and oblique leaf bases set this species apart.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFC8DFF145906956D" blockId="10.[856,1510,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
The label from the 
<typeStatus id="54AE8871FFEA823AFBCEFF1558399492" box="[1075,1122,161,182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">type</typeStatus>
collection describes the fruits as cordate (
<emphasis id="B961EAC1FFEA823AFC6BFF09587994F6" box="[918,1058,189,210]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">fructu cordato</emphasis>
). It is difficult to know what Eggers saw in three dimensions based on the single fruit on the isotype at A, but Egger’s notes suggest that the fruits may have been flattened and, therefore, possibly somewhat like those of the ground-trailing species in shape (i.e. 
<figureCitation id="132E2A56FFEA823AFB22FE87590A956D" box="[1247,1361,307,329]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="2.[184,220,1816,1835]" captionTargetBox="[160,1504,158,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[160,1504,158,1791]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIG.1. Flowers fruits, and habit of Solanum sect. Herpystichum: A. Solanum limoncochaense, habit, flower, and bud. B. S. limoncochaense fruit in situ and C. in cross section (E. J. Tepe &amp; S. Stern 2627, QCNE). D. S. trifolium flower and leaf (E. J. Tepe &amp; S. Stern 2682, QCNE). E. S. phaseoloides habit, flower, and leaf (photo by W. H. Haber). F. S. crassinervium habit (E. J. Tepe &amp; S. Stern 2729, QCNE), and G. flowers (S. Stern &amp; E. J. Tepe 400, QCNE). H. S. evolvulifolium habit and flower, and I. fruit (immature) (E. J. Tepe &amp; S. Stern 2671, QCNE). J. S. pacificum inflorescence with flowers, buds, and fruit (immature), and K. habit (E. J. Tepe et al. 2696, QCNE). L. S. loxophyllum habit, note adventitious roots at nodes, and M. older stem with inflorescences, note figure eightshaped stem (E. J. Tepe &amp; S. Stern 2726, QCNE). Inflorescences emerge from the cleft between the two lobes of the stem." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6327848" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6327848/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Figs. 1B–C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA36D3FFEA823AFC8DFEE45F9A96E2" blockId="10.[856,1510,160,2001]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">
The collections of this species from eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3027643FFEA823AFAAAFEE459EB9542" box="[1367,1456,336,358]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
differ somewhat from the 
<typeStatus id="54AE8871FFEA823AFBABFEDA58DE95A7" box="[1110,1157,366,387]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">type</typeStatus>
in that they have longer pubescence, darker stems that are densely sand-punctate (vs. light tan, non-punctate stems), inflorescences with less dense and coarser pubescence, and non-punctate calyces. The Peruvian collection is closer to the 
<typeStatus id="54AE8871FFEA823AFB90FE5758C795DC" box="[1133,1180,483,504]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">type</typeStatus>
in leaf shape than collections from eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3027643FFEA823AFC0DFDB458129632" box="[1008,1097,512,534]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1077">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, but the plant appears to be rather fleshy. It is possible that the two variants from the regions east of the Andes merit recognition at the species level; however, they have no unambiguous, qualitative differences and, since this species has been collected few times, there is currently insufficient material upon which to base further taxonomic decisions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
